Specilist SDET :

✅ 1. Reproduce the Issue

Launch the application manually in Firefox.
Compare behavior step‑by‑step with Chrome.
Capture screenshots, console logs, and network logs where the issue appears.

This gives you a baseline.

✅ 2. Check Browser Console Errors (Critical Step)
In Firefox Developer Tools:

Console → Errors/Warnings

Look for TypeError, SyntaxError, CORS issues
Check for unsupported JS functions like innerText, event.path, Promise.any(), etc.


Network → Failed requests

4xx/5xx API errors
Redirect loops
Cross-domain blocked requests



Many UI issues arise due to:

JS engine differences
CSP restrictions
HTTP/HTTPS mixed content
Unhandled DOM events incompatible with Firefox


✅ 3. Validate Selector/Locator Compatibility
Some DOM properties behave differently in Firefox.
For example:

innerText works differently → better to use .getText() or textContent.
XPath indexing may differ.
Elements not clickable due to overlay or CSS differences.

In automation:

Check if Selenium throws:

ElementNotInteractable
ElementClickIntercepted
ElementNotVisible



Try:
Javanew Actions(driver).moveToElement(element).click().perform();Show more lines
Or use JS click temporarily (only for debugging):
Java((JavascriptExecutor)driver).executeScript("arguments[0].click();", element);Show more lines

✅ 4. Validate UI Rendering / CSS Differences
Firefox interprets CSS differently than Chrome.
Check:

Flexbox rendering
Grid alignment
z-index issues
Vendor prefixes (e.g. -webkit- won’t work in Firefox)

Use Firefox DevTools:

Inspect element → Layout → Check if element is hidden or behind other layers.


✅ 5. Browser-Specific JavaScript Behavior
Firefox may not support:

Certain ECMAScript features (older versions)
Chrome-specific APIs (e.g., WebKit APIs)
Unhandled events like event.path

Check:

JS errors in console
Polyfills missing (e.g., for fetch, Promise, etc.)

If needed, ask dev team to include polyfills:
JavaScriptimport 'core-js/stable';import 'regenerator-runtime/runtime';Show more lines

✅ 6. Validate Application Config Differences
Sometimes:

Firefox blocks 3rd-party cookies
CORS policies behave differently
Mixed content (HTTP inside HTTPS) blocked

Check:

Authentication redirects
Cookies (SameSite=None; Secure)
LocalStorage or sessionStorage issues


✅ 7. Validate Selenium WebDriver Compatibility
Make sure:

You are using the correct Geckodriver version
Firefox browser version matches driver compatibility
Selenium version supports Firefox version

Update everything:
Selenium 4.x
Geckodriver latest
Firefox latest


✅ 8. Compare Response Codes in Chrome vs Firefox
Using Network tab:

Check if API responses differ
Sometimes Firefox blocks insecure endpoints
Some APIs return different headers in Firefox (CORS)

Example cause:
Access-Control-Allow-Origin missing in Firefox


✅ 9. Try Running the Same Scenario Headless
This helps isolate rendering issues.
JavaFirefoxOptions options = new FirefoxOptions();options.setHeadless(true);Show more lines
If headless works → UI rendering is the problem.

✅ 10. Document the Findings
Prepare a report for developers:
Include:

Browser version
Firefox logs
Screenshots
Network failures
JS errors
Steps to reproduce
Comparisons with Chrome behavior

My approach would be to reproduce the issue in Firefox and compare it with Chrome, then check Firefox console logs, network calls, and JS errors to identify any browser‑specific issues. I would validate Selenium locators, CSS rendering, browser configurations, CORS policies, and cookie behavior because these often differ across browsers. I would also verify driver versions (Geckodriver) and ensure cross‑browser compatibility. Finally, I would document my findings clearly for the development team.
