⭐ Code Review Best Practices

 Review for Logic & Correctness First
Focus on whether the code actually does what it’s supposed to do:

Validate business logic
Check edge cases and error handling
Ensure the code meets the requirement/acceptance criteria
Confirm no functionality is broken

👉 Don’t start with naming/style—start with correctness.

2️⃣ Ensure Code Readability & Maintainability
Readable code reduces long‑term cost:

Clear naming conventions
Small, meaningful functions
Avoid deeply nested logic
Remove unused imports, commented code, dead code
Use consistent formatting

👉 If a new developer can understand it in one pass, it’s good.

3️⃣ Check for Test Coverage
As an SDET, this is important:

Verify unit tests, integration tests, and automation tests cover all paths
Check edge cases & negative scenarios
Ensure tests are not flaky
Confirm mocks/stubs are used correctly
Validate naming + readability of test cases

👉 Code without tests should not be approved.

4️⃣ Verify Code Follows SOLID & Clean Code Principles

Single Responsibility
Open/Closed
Liskov Substitution
Interface Segregation
Dependency Inversion

Also check:

DRY (Don’t Repeat Yourself)
KISS (Keep It Simple)
YAGNI (You Aren’t Gonna Need It)

👉 This ensures scalable, maintainable architecture.

5️⃣ Check Performance & Optimization

Avoid unnecessary loops
Use streams/collections properly
Ensure database queries are efficient
Avoid large objects in memory unnecessarily
Optimize API calls

👉 Performance issues often hide inside small code changes.

6️⃣ Security Is Critical
Review for:

SQL injection (use prepared statements)
XSS/CSRF protection
Secrets/credentials not in code
Proper authentication & authorization checks
Validation on user input
Safe handling of sensitive data

👉 NEVER allow hardcoded passwords, tokens, or URLs.

7️⃣ Cross‑Browser / Platform Compatibility (UI code)
For frontend or automation:

Confirm selectors are stable
Avoid brittle XPath
Ensure browser compatibility (Chrome, Firefox, Edge)
Validate waits & synchronization
Test responsive behavior


8️⃣ Review API Contracts Carefully

Validate request/response schema
Check error codes & messages
Validate header/auth usage
Ensure backward compatibility
Verify idempotency where required
Versioning is respected


9️⃣ Small, Incremental Reviews Only
Prefer small PRs:

Easier to understand
Faster to review
Fewer merge conflicts
Less chance of introducing bugs

👉 PRs beyond 400–500 lines should be rejected or split.

🔟 Give Constructive & Respectful Feedback

Be clear, specific, and objective
Avoid personal comments
Explain the why, not just the what
Suggest alternatives when pointing out a problem
Encourage learning, not blaming

👉 Code review is a collaboration, not criticism.

1️⃣1️⃣ Use Checklists
A standard checklist ensures nothing is missed.
Example items:

Functionality
Error handling
Input validation
Coding standards
Tests
Security risks
Logging/tracing
Performance considerations


1️⃣2️⃣ Approve Only When All Criteria Are Met
Do not approve if:

There is insufficient test coverage
Code is unclear
Logic is questionable
Security issues exist
Requirements are incomplete

