 Deep-Dive Checklist by Area
1) Test Architecture & Patterns

UI: Use Page Objects/Screenplay; pages expose actions, not locators.
API: Client wrappers for endpoints; schema validation (JSON schema); contract tests.
Services: Layered tests—unit → integration → contract → E2E; use testcontainers locally.
Mobile: Page Objects for screens; stable selectors (Accessibility IDs); no coordinate taps.

Red flags: Test does DB manipulation directly; tests know too much about UI structure; duplicate locators.

2) Code Quality & Readability

Style: Linters/formatters configured (e.g., ESLint/Prettier, Black/flake8, Checkstyle).
Naming: test_should_do_X_when_Y pattern; helper methods named for behavior.
Structure: Small test methods, clear arrange‑act‑assert sections; no nested logic in assertions.
DRY: Common flows in helpers/fixtures; no duplicated setup across tests.

Red flags: Magic numbers/timeouts; complicated setup inside test method; excessive conditionals.

3) Stability & Flakiness

Use explicit waits (e.g., WebDriverWait / ExpectedConditions) over sleeps.
Adopt polling utilities with max timeout; exponential backoff for eventual consistency.
Idempotent retries only where safe (e.g., GET with eventual consistency).
Randomized data seeded for determinism; control time with clock abstraction.

Red flags: Thread.sleep(5000); order-dependent tests; shared state across tests.

4) Assertions & Test Value

Assertions check business outcomes, not just superficial states.
Verify side effects (DB rows, emitted events, emails) via test doubles or observability.
Avoid brittle UI assertions (exact text blocks); prefer semantic checks (roles/labels/states).
Use soft assertions where multiple validations in one flow, but fail fast for critical ones.

Red flags: Only HTTP 200 asserted; no negative/edge tests; asserts on transient UI text.

5) Test Data, Fixtures & Teardown

Isolation: Each test owns its data (create → use → delete); avoid relying on preseeded data.
Factories/Builders: Generate domain objects; avoid massive JSON inline blocks.
Teardown: Guaranteed cleanup (afterEach/afterAll); handles failures.
Idempotency: Re‑run safety; no cumulative pollution.

Red flags: Shared “user123” across suite; brittle UUIDs copied; missing cleanup leading to leaks.

6) CI/CD Integration

Fast feedback: Unit/contract tests on PR; E2E nightly or gated.
Parallelism: Test sharding; containerized runners; proper resource limits.
Artifacts: Upload screenshots, logs, HAR files, videos on failure.
Flake tracking: Quarantine tag + dashboard; auto-retry policy documented.

Red flags: Long-running PR builds (>15 min) without parallelization; missing artifacts.

7) Security & Secrets

Secrets in env or secret manager; never in code or test logs.
Sanitize logs/reports; redact tokens and personal data.
Use least privilege test credentials; rotate periodically.
Static analysis (SAST) and dependency checks (SCA) integrated.

Red flags: Bearer abc123 in source; screenshots showing PII; committing .env.

8) Performance & Scalability

For API/load tests: define SLAs; run smoke perf in CI, deep perf in pipeline stage.
Page load and core action timings captured; thresholds enforced.
Avoid N+1 waits or repeated heavy setups; cache where acceptable in test scope.

Red flags: Test times ballooning; hidden loops with network calls.

9) Accessibility (UI)

Use accessibility IDs/selectors; basic a11y checks (contrast, roles, labels).
Integrate linters (axe-core/pa11y) for critical flows where feasible.

Red flags: Reliance on XPath by position; missing labels/roles.

10) Reporting & Observability

Consistent report format (JUnit/Allure/Extent); attach context (screenshot/video/log).
Failure messages include enough hints to reproduce.
Structured logs (JSON) and correlation IDs across layers where feasible.

Red flags: “AssertionError: expected true to be true”; no artifacts on failure.

